### 4. GREEN framework
*   **Presenter**: Marisol Palmero
*   **Slides**: [GREEN framework](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-green-green-framework-00)
*   **Draft**: [draft-ietf-green-framework](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-green-framework/) (v02)
*   Marisol Palmero presented structural cleanups in the reference model. Notably, the "main network manager" layer was renamed to "Energy Management System" (EMS) to align with older RFCs.
*   Key updates in v02:
    *   Added an EMAN migration mapping table.
    *   Introduced an "operational considerations" section to define inheritance rules for unit multipliers and data source accuracy to minimize telemetry payload bloat.
    *   Added a functional relationship type mapping: "enabled-by" and "enabling" (originally raised by Tony Li) to represent logical or hardware-hosting dependencies (e.g., a chassis hosting a line card) distinct from direct power or metering relationships.
*   The team will continue to focus on the alignment with device-level and future controller-level YANG models.

### 5. Update on YANG base model & Controller Scoping
*   **Presenters**: Benoit Claise & Jan Lindblad
*   **Slides**: [Update on YANG base model -- Benoit Claise -- Jan Lindblad](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-green-update-on-yang-base-model-benoit-claise-jan-lindblad-00)
*   **Draft**: [draft-ietf-green-power-and-energy-yang](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-green-power-and-energy-yang/) (v03)
*   Benoit Claise detailed changes in the base device model, which is split into operational (read-only) and energy control (read-write) sections.
*   **Relationship Mapping**: Relationships use a string-type Peer ID instead of a UUID because routers often cannot resolve the UUID of adjacent devices natively (e.g., via LLDP or CDP).
*   **Open Technical Issues**:
    *   *Instantaneous Power Mandatory vs. Optional*: The current draft defines instantaneous power as mandatory. However, hardware constraints make it impossible or too costly to measure instantaneous power on all components. Rob Wilton and Nigel Davis suggested making the YANG leaf optional but adding conditional guidelines (e.g., "if a physical sensor is present, the node must report it"). 
    *   *Data Types*: Tony Li pointed out that instantaneous power is defined as an `int32`, which allows negative power. He suggested changing it to `uint32` unless there are science-fiction use cases for negative power. Benoit Claise agreed to refine this.
    *   *Dual vs. Single Multipliers*: The team will take to the mailing list whether consumed and delivered energy require separate unit multipliers.
*   **Controller-level YANG Model**: Jan Lindblad presented on the emerging work for a controller-level YANG model (Work Item 1 & 4). The model is designed to be a Minimum Viable Draft (MVD) focusing on configuring data sources, scheduling telemetry collection, correlation of IDs between controllers and devices, data transformations (sums, averages, peaks), and exporting to external databases.
*   **Poll**:
    *   *Should the base network controller model be scoped to include more than just power/energy attributes?*
        *   **Yes**: 16
        *   **No**: 2
        *   **No opinion**: 5
        *   **Total**: 54
    *   *Result*: Strong support to scope the base network controller model beyond simple power/energy attributes. Rob Wilton advised the authors to still focus on power and energy first in the initial drafts while leaving extensible hooks.

### 6. PETRA Green API
*   **Presenter**: Luis Miguel Contreras Murillo
*   **Slides**: [Update on draft-petra-green-api](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-green-update-on-draft-petra-green-api-00)
*   **Draft**: `draft-petra-green-api`
*   Luis Miguel Contreras Murillo provided an update on the Path Energy Traffic Radio API (PETRA). PETRA acts as an Northbound Interface (NBI) from a network controller, allowing external consumers (such as SD-WAN customers) to request energy consumption statistics between specific endpoints.
*   Updates in this version:
    *   Removed out-of-scope parameters (e.g., carbon intensity) to align with GREEN's charter (such work will move to the Sustain-RG).
    *   Generalized the API to query by IP prefixes, MAC addresses (L2), and network slice service delivery points.
    *   Added traffic throughput and volume characterizing metrics.
*   **Polls**:
    *   *Have you read/reviewed any version of the PETRA draft (draft-petra-green-api)?*
        *   **Yes**: 12
        *   **No**: 12
        *   **No opinion**: 0
        *   **Total**: 55
    *   *Do you think that the WG should adopt the petra draft at this time?*
        *   **Yes**: 11
        *   **No**: 0
        *   **No opinion**: 16
        *   **Total**: 55
    *   *Result*: There was interest in adopting the PETRA draft. The chairs will take the adoption call to the mailing list, reminding the group that core deliverables remain the priority.

### 7. YANG Data Model for Reporting Utilization Scores in ISAC
*   **Presenter**: Mehad
*   **Slides**: [A YANG Data Model for Reporting Utilization Scores in ISAC](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-green-a-yang-data-model-for-reporting-utilization-scores-in-isac-00)
*   **Draft**: `draft-jadoon-green-isac-utilization`
*   Mehad presented a model targeting Integrated Sensing and Communication (ISAC). ISAC components consume significant compute, power, memory, and storage resources. The proposed model reports an overall utilization score and augments the GREEN base power/energy module.
*   **Discussion**: Jan Lindblad noted that augmenting the device-level model makes sense, but cautioned that representing service-level concepts on the controller side is highly distinct. Another participant questioned how easy it is to isolate the power consumption of "sensing" versus the underlying radio access network (RAN) components, especially during idle/night periods where sensing prevents the RAN from going into deep sleep.
*   **Poll**:
    *   *Have you read/reviewed any version of the ISAC Utilization Draft (draft-jadoon-green-isac-utilization)?*
        *   **Yes**: 6
        *   **No**: 23
        *   **No opinion**: 1
        *   **Total**: 54
    *   *Result*: Since only a few people have read the draft, the chairs deferred any adoption poll and urged participants to review the draft on the mailing list.

### 8. GREEN Provenance
*   **Presenter**: Marisol Palmero
*   **Slides**: [GREEN provenance](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-green-green-provenance-00)
*   **Draft**: `draft-palmero-green-provenance`
*   Marisol Palmero introduced a draft exploring the application of telemetry provenance (signing data at the source/controller using COSE signatures) to energy and power metrics. This prevents "greenwashing" by guaranteeing that reported data is authentic, auditable, and traceably verified.
*   **Discussion**: Ben Curtis asked about verification failures (e.g., if a signature fails or is missing, should the controller drop the telemetry completely?). Mahesh Jethanandani (AD) raised a scoping question, asking if this work belongs in GREEN or if it is a general mechanism that should be standardized in the Ops Area Working Group (OPSAWG). Marisol agreed that while the signing technology is generic, the energy audit trail use case is a key driver within GREEN.

### 9. Multicast Eco-Mode Signaling
*   **Presenter**: Luis Miguel Contreras Murillo
*   **Slides**: [draft-contreras-pim-eco-mode](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-green-draft-contreras-pim-eco-mode-00)
*   **Draft**: `draft-contreras-pim-eco-mode`
*   Luis Miguel Contreras Murillo presented a PIM working group draft on extending IGMP/MLD signaling (RFC 9279) to allow subscribers to signal an "eco-mode" preference for multicast video streams. 
*   The draft introduces four Eco Levels (0: No eco, 1: Low impact optimizations, 2: Moderate quality trade-offs, 3: High eco with reduced resolution/quality) and preferences like carbon awareness and renewable energy.
*   **Discussion**: Rob Wilton found the concept interesting and suggested refining the differences between Level 0 and Level 1 (since most devices optimize energy by default if there is no service impact) and simplifying the preference fields.

### 10. Hackathon Results
*   **Presenter**: Luis Miguel Contreras Murillo
*   **Slides**: [Report on recent Hackathon results](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-green-report-on-recent-hackathon-results-00)
*   Luis Miguel Contreras Murillo summarized experiments conducted in the Telefonica lab. Two physical routers were connected with various traffic flows (100G, 5x10G, 4x40G) to compare CLI-reported internal power measurements against external smart PDU readings.
*   **Key Results**: 
    *   A ~6% to 10% discrepancy was observed between CLI and PDU values. David Slik suggested in the chat that this is likely because the smart PDU measures AC input power, while the router internal sensors measure DC output power after power supply unit losses.
    *   Idle power consumption remains very high across typical routing hardware.
    *   Incremental traffic added a modest but noticeable energy footprint (~10W per 100G per hop).
*   Future hackathons will test actual YANG Push streaming and sleep-mode transitions.

### 11. IPFIX Energy Consumption Export
*   **Presenter**: Jinjie Yan
*   **Slides**: [draft-yan-opsawg-ipfix-energy-consumption](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-green-draft-yan-opsawg-ipfix-energy-consumption-00)
*   **Draft**: `draft-yan-opsawg-ipfix-energy-consumption`
*   Jinjie Yan proposed exporting energy metrics via IPFIX. The motivation is to correlate transient power spikes directly with flow metering events at the source without post-processing or polling delays. The draft's information elements are aligned semantically with [draft-ietf-green-power-and-energy-yang](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-green-power-and-energy-yang/).
*   **Discussion**: Rob Wilton expressed skepticism, noting that IPFIX also operates on configured export intervals or packet counters. He questioned why IPFIX represents a superior solution to YANG Push for capturing transient spikes. Jinjie Yan agreed to elaborate on the technical benefits and discuss this further on the mailing list.

